{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491170"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:36:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:36:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"854"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/854"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.04,0.82,0.11,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31050"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/854"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16926"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4972"},{"type":"tags","id":"11590"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6374"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44625"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31050"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old recent migrant from Malaysia presents with chronic left-sided, dull lower abdominal pain. She does not have any other symptoms at present, but she has had episodes of fever with rigors and chills for the last few months. Her medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes, for which she takes perindopril and metformin. On examination her blood pressure is 132/84 mmHg, pulse 76/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A plain abdominal radiograph is performed (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic pancreatitis","Diverticulitis","Staghorn calculus","Tuberculous lymphadenopathy","Faecolith"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe radiograph clearly shows a large \u003Cstrong\u003Estaghorn calculus\u003C/strong\u003E and several other smaller calculi occupying much of the left renal collecting system. There is also a calcified structure within the pelvis, which is probably a bladder calculus. The episodes of lower abdominal pain and fever suggest recurrent urinary infections, which would explain the development of the renal tract calculi. A staghorn calculus obtains a characteristic shape by forming a cast of the renal pelvis and calyces, thus resembling the horns of a stag. Although all types of urinary stones can result in the formation of staghorn calculi, but majority of them are composed of a struvite-carbonate-apatite matrix. Struvite is magnesium ammonium phosphate. Renal calculus disease is relatively common in countries such as Malaysia, where 10-15% of stones will be struvite in origin. These are formed usually as the result of recurrent urinary tract infections. These stones can remain asymptomatic but most will present with symptoms including flank pain, recurrent urinary tract infections or haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a continuing, chronic, inflammatory process of the pancreas. The symptoms include intermittent attacks of severe pain, in the mid-abdomen or left upper abdomen radiating to the midback, diarrhoea and weight loss. Characteristic radiological appearances include calcium deposits in the pancreas, which is not the case in this X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst this patient\u0027s episode of pain and fever could be due to episodes \u003Cstrong\u003Ediverticulitis, \u003C/strong\u003Ethis diagnosis would not explain the areas of calcification on the plain abdominal X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E faecolith \u003C/strong\u003Eis an inspissated mass of compacted faeces, usually found in the colon. Faecoliths can cause luminal obstruction of the appendix, increasing the risk of appendicitis and perforation. Sometimes they can have a rim of calcification and be visible on a plain X-ray. The areas of calcification do not resemble faecoliths.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst this patient comes from a region where tuberculosis is endemic, the radiological appearances of the areas of calcification do not fit for \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberculous lymphadenopathy, \u003C/strong\u003Ewhere\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ethe para-aortic nodes might be calcified.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Staghorn calculi are a relatively common form of calcification in patients with chronic or recurrent urinary tract infections."],"references":["Terry RS, Preminger GM. Metabolic evaluation and medical management of staghorn calculi. sian J Urol 2020; 2:122-29."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16926"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"854"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18625"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18625"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7be19fcf-b853-46c9-a310-72c15d3ed7b6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7be19fcf-b853-46c9-a310-72c15d3ed7b6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":340,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16926","links":{"self":"https: